In France, voting rights have traditionally been a low technology experience: the electors go into a booth alone, putting a pre-printed sheet of paper indicating their candidate’s choice in an envelope.
After officials confirm the identity of the voter, the voter let the envelope down in the voice box and signs the voice call.
French election law has quite strict codification of the court proceedings.
Since 1988, voting boxes must be transparent, so that voters and observers can testify that no envelopes are present at the start of the vote and that no envelopes are added except those that are carefully spoken and from approved voting rights.
